This article is about an executive order issued by President Obama in March 2015, titled "Planning for Federal Sustainability in the Next Decade." The order aims to maintain federal leadership in sustainability and greenhouse gas emission reductions. It sets policies for federal agencies to increase efficiency and improve environmental performance, with a goal of reducing agency direct greenhouse gas emissions by at least 40% over the next decade. The order also emphasizes the importance of renewable or alternative energy solutions and outlines specific targets and goals for agencies in areas such as energy conservation, water use efficiency, fleet management, building efficiency, and sustainable acquisition and procurement. The order also establishes various duties and responsibilities for the Chair of the Council on Environmental Quality, the Director of the Office of Management and Budget, the Federal Chief Sustainability Officer, and agency heads. The article includes definitions of key terms used in the order and notes that it is not intended to create any legal rights or benefits.